title: Five stars *after* a slight modification.
text:
This product worked perfectly with a few modifications. If you get this part and it doesn't seem to fit and bends slightly outward at the ends, then read on (and be ready to grab a file or hacksaw).

A few other reviewers have mentioned the protruding circular knobs near each end of the part. For our specific Whirlpool refrigerator, there must have been a minor design change since there were no detents for this protrusion to fit into causing the part to bend slightly inward -- enough for the drawer not to fit.

As others have said, once these small plastic knobs were removed (personally, I used a small hacksaw to remove the protruding bit), the part worked exactly as the original part.

Even though my satisfaction with the part rates a 5-star review, I decided to give this 1-star because of the way I typically read ratings. If I see an average rating of 4-5 stars, I might read one or two, but then I focus on the lower-rated reviews to get a better idea of problems with the product that the others may not have seen.

If you're reading this, then, just a heads-up that you may need to slightly modify the part in order to get it to fit -- then it's a 5 of 5.

You can look at my pictures and see how easy it is to do and everybody likes fresh ground coffee as opposed to coffee that's been sitting in a pod for who knows how long.

It's also exceptional in the fact that it does not leak. I have a reusable pod that I can just put coffee grounds in and put it in my pot. But then the water always leaks all over the place. I like the fact that this product has a tight seal and does not leak.

And I think for a week it would still retain fresh flavor.

Whoops I buy this again? Well I really don't even like my coffee maker that much. I got the coffee maker for free last Christmas and I'm always aggravated that you have to pay so much for pods. It's also not that great when you're having a get together, because making one cuppa coffee at a time can be quite aggravating when you've got 40 people here. So I just don't know. I guess if the price was right I might buy them just for personal use. That being said I look forward to this coffeepot dying all together. Then I can just go back to the regular old coffee pot.

title: Defeats the purpose of a Keurig
text:
A Keurig will give you a great cup of coffee, but you don't need a Keurig for that. What makes a Keurig unique is that it brews a cup of coffee faster and easier than any other method -- no carafe to clean, no filters to purchase, and no need to grind beans or measure ground coffee. Just pop in a K-cup and presto! In about two minutes you have coffee. Cleanup is restricted to your cup (and throwing away the used K-cup).

Using a "My K-cup" filter assembly with your own coffee really defeats the purpose of having a Keurig. You have to remove the original assembly (don't lose it!), measure your own coffee (which takes adjustment; you'll probably go through several cups of coffee before you get the measurement to your satisfaction), and clean everything up afterward (it can make a bit of a mess). This is really about as much trouble as just using a conventional little drip coffeemaker. In fact, to me it is MORE trouble, although I think the Keurig uses a bit less coffee and could save some money.

So there you have it. Using a Keurig in the conventional way is the most convenient but also the most expensive way to brew coffee, but using a My K-cup filter saves money at the expense of the convenience.

title: Works Great, No Modifications Required!
text:
I've had my Keurig for 2 years, and my re-usable K-cup for 1 year. It works perfectly just as it is, as long as you don't overfill it and follow the directions.

Oh, wait...mine didn't HAVE directions.

When I first got it, I won't lie...I screwed it all up. The blasted thing didn't have directions, so I thought the cute little basket went right into the K-cup part of the Keurig. I had not a clue that the black K-cup holder part with the needle that pokes the bottom of the K-cup had to come OUT of my Keurig to put the gray part in.

I made a huge mess.

So, here are the directions for everyone else, so you don't have to be a dummy like me:

1. That place in your Keurig where K-cups normally go? Yeah, it actually comes out of the machine. Really, it does. There are three little tabs you have to push on the rim of it to pull it out. Get that thing out of there. It's not difficult, so if you're being rough with it, stop. It comes out pretty easily. Be careful you don't gouge yourself with the stabby-thingies in the machine.

2. Open up your reusable gray K-cup filter, wash it, and put about a tablespoon of coffee in there. If you like it strong like me, I suggest a finer grind. If you use Folgers, put it on a smaller cup setting or you won't get it very strong. This little bugger is made for just one cup at a time (whereas I can usually get one big cup or two little cups out of a disposable K-cup).

3. PUT THE LID BACK ON (!!!) the gray K-cup filter and put it into the spot where the regular black one usually lives (amazing, it fits!). Close it up and let 'er rip.

4. If you got coffee everywhere, you did something wrong. I know, I know...I didn't want to believe it either. Maybe you didn't put the lid on, or put the cute little basket into the machine without the gray part. Whatever. Either way, it's not the product's fault that you're dumb like me. :o) Start over, figure out what you messed up, and enjoy your coffee when you finally have that forehead-slap moment.

title: Nice filter that works with almost any container, bad pitcher
text:
We mostly buy bottled water or when available fill our water bottles at the machines in front of grocery stores. Occasionally when we're running a bit low and I want to make a pitcher of iced tea I'll use tap water so we still have water. Every time I do I think of all of the current news stories involving dangerous or even poisonous tap water. I figured a filter, any filter, can only help. The fact that this comes with a pitcher and a filter that can be used with the pitcher or with almost anything else you have in the house was a bonus.

The pitcher is a serious disappointment to me. If were rating it alone, it'd get 1 star. The spout that closes for pouring has a gap in that allows water to pour out even when closed -- though it doesn't snap closed so if you bump the pitcher a little the spout flaps all around. The plastic feels cheap. It really need a different lid that doesn't pop off so easily. That's the bad.

The good is the filter itself is easy to use. It can be used in almost any pitcher or bottle you have at home. In fact If it's possible, I'd recommend buying the filter section without the pitcher. It has markings so you can see what month you starting using the filter. Although you CAN filter water fast, if you're not fond of wasting water I'd actually do it at a slower steady stream as the filter itself does not hold a lot of water so a lot of water is literally going down the drain as it pours out over the filter. At a slower pace I filled the pitched quite a bit slower but wasted a lot less.

In the end, I'd recommend the filter itself but not the pitcher.

title: Top Rated By Me & Everything You Want To Know About This Washer
text:
Kenmore 27" Top-Load Washer with Triple Action Impeller and 4.8 Cubic Ft. Total Capacity, White is a very highly top rated machine by me. I will first tell you that I was a dry cleaning/laundry Inspector for half a decade, so you will know my expertise in my review of this beautiful machine. Before buying this washing machine, I owned a Whirlpool Calypso HE washer, which just died after 20 years of weekly use. The secret to keeping a machine running for 20 years- luck, use a surge protector that is made for washing machines (protects those circuit boards), run an empty load with a cup of vinegar to keep it clean inside at least once or twice a year and always load it properly with not too much soap. I do read reviews before buying anything here on Amazon and other websites and that helps greatly in my decision making.

Before I received this machine, I measured all the doorways, as our house is small and have narrow doors. The machine is a hair over 27 inches wide, and my doorways 28 inches after removing the doors. Amazon delivered it perfect- being slow and careful having only close to ½ inch on each side of the doorways. I was very happy with Amazon's skilled delivery team. The set up takes a bit of time (I did this), as you want it as level as you can get it. I first hooked up the drain hose. There is a drain hose with clamp included, BUT, this drain hose is a very short 28 inches long, with the curved part that goes into the wash tub 23 inches long. The opening of the drain to this washer is on the back- bottom right side of this machine, 6 inches above the floor. I needed a 10 foot drain hose to go all the way behind the machine, along the side and up to the laundry tub, then into it. I ordered one here on Amazon which took a couple days. It's perfect! So, please note- DRAIN HOSE INCLUDED IS VERY SHORT! The good part was, they included 3 metal circular clamps that worked perfect on the 10 foot hose, so I only needed to buy the hose and use one of the clamps.

I then, attached a grounding wire (our home is old), the water hoses (NOT INCLUDED) and plugged it in. Now, I adjusted the machine from the back wall (evenly on each side) to leave just enough room for the drain hose on the floor. When, I had it perfect, I marked around the machine corners on the floor with tape, so after moving it to adjust the legs, I can place it back perfectly. The legs of the machine can be adjusted on the legs- NOT the base feet on the floor, just above the base feet with a 3/4 inch wrench. You'll need a short 2 by 4 board to hold the washer up while adjusting the legs. Check every so often with a level on the sides and top (directions in booklet), until it's as level as you can get it. Now, turn on the water hoses, and while running your first load you can check for any leaks from the water lines and drain line.

I opened the beautiful clear lid and loaded my laundry. When you load, place items in evenly around the center (not bunched up), and as you load, VERY lightly push down (as the tub tilts easily). You do not want clothes around the center that can fall over, making the machine out of balance. You always want to see the center of the tub when finished. The tub in this washer is a huge 23 inches wide by 20 inches deep. I then added my detergent- less than you think. I had to remove the liquid-only inside cup of the detergent drawer to just use powder. I use a few tablespoons per load. And should you need to rinse clothes before washing, there is a Faucet Button! Then, I closed the lid. Push Power, select the load- I first chose Towels (for towels, sheets, socks and underthings), the cycle came up Heavy Duty and the water very warm. I can also add a variety of other things such as Extra Rinse, or change the water temperature. Once ready, I hold the Start button for a couple seconds, as it counts down to zero. The lid locks and that's it.

I watched all the cycles with this washer and this is where I was impressed. The spraying action comes from 9 jets all around the machine. The wash basket moves in a circular motion BOTH ways if it needs more balance. The impeller action moves it back and forth. And talk about the water fill- THE WATER COVERS THE CLOTHES! It takes time to clean so well with enough water- this load took about an hour and 15 minutes. As for my regular shirts, slacks, blouses and pants. I have always put these in net bags. I have all sizes from small to really big enough for a couple pairs of pants. I learned from my Inspector job that all machines can be rough on my regular clothing, but not with net bags. They keep my clothes perfect. I used the Delicate Load and only changed the Cold water to Warm. This load took 50 minutes. When done, the machine tells you on the LCD board. When I removed my clothes, I immediately noticed they smelled so clean and looked like new. I mean bright, beautiful colors with no dinginess. The difference from this washer to other Impellers- water that covers the clothes in both wash and rinse (my old Whirlpool mainly sprayed leaving dry spots, where I saw this one cover the clothes in water completely), No lint all over the clothes (my old machine left lint always), clothes are super bright and smell super clean and it takes more time to really clean clothes. As for blankets, this machine is outstanding with it's huge capacity. Just put it around the bottom evenly, gently pushing down and then wash on Bulky. My Queen Comforters came out beautiful, bright, clean and smelling lovely.

The last thing I wanted to find out, is who made this machine and where? The model number that starts with 110 means it was made by Whirlpool. (Those that start with 417 are made by Frigidaire). Since 2017, Kenmore products have been made by other manufacturers. I was happy with this, as I've always liked Whirlpool. And it was made in Ohio, of course where the parts come from is another story. But being put together here in the USA also made me happy. This is a top rated machine by me, which gave me sparkling clean clothes from actually using more water. 5 STARS.

title: 100% Accurate For Temperature And 99% Accurate For Humidity
text:
I have owned several different Temperature/Humidity meters over the years. Since every room in the house has a different humidity reading depending on how many windows are in the room or which direction it faces, we always like to know the humidity to keep the rooms all more normal and similar. We have the worst humidity in a bedroom on the north wall with large windows. For anyone with any collectibles, keeping the humidity out of the room means not damaging your collectibles or items from too much damp or mildew.

My brother has an expensive weather meter system, as he has a large collection of remote control planes- many fabric made, so I always have something 100% accurate to compare my meters to. This Amprobe Relative Humidity & Temperature Meter is actually the most accurate meter I have ever owned. We tested this inside, outside, even in crawl spaces and duct work to see the results. The temperature was always 100% accurate, whether it was ambient, dew point or wet bulb.

As for the humidity temperature readings- we found this Amprobe to be off by 1/2 to 1 % depending on where the reading was taken. Inside duct work- it was off by only 1/2 %, but in a room or outside it was off by 1%. This is the most accurate meter I have ever owned. I had owned a Pyle meter that was always off by 6-10%, and a Fluke that was off by 4-6 % on the humidity readings. My best meter before this Amprobe was made by Ambient Weather- the humidity was off by just 2 %. The temperature readings on all my meters was always pretty accurate- it's the humidity readings that are never completely accurate.

This Amprobe THWD-3 Relative Humidity and Temperature Meter comes with the meter itself, a removable protective metal sensor cap, black carrying case with belt loop, 9 V battery, User's Manual and a Wet Bulb Chart. There is an On/Off Switch- which automatically turns off should you forget to turn it off after 30 minutes. The Min/Max button allows you to use it for memory. The Hold button allows you to hold the present reading. The DP/WB button gives you the Dew Point Temperature or Wet Bulb Temperature- which came out 100% accurate. The last button is for your readings in either Celsius or Fahrenheit temperatures. There is also a Low Battery Warning picture.

Besides being the most accurate Temperature/Humidity Meter I have owned to date, I found when you remove the protective metal sensor cap, the reading is given in a few seconds- way faster than with the cap on. You just have to take more care that the sensor is not damaged when the cap is off. This is a great, well made, extremely accurate temperature and humidity meter and is definitely worth 5 Stars, being the most accurate meter I have ever owned, and Amprobe even warrants this meter for a year, making it well worth buying.

title: For that perfect cup of coffee!
text:
I seriously think these stainless pour over coffee filters/drippers are one of the greatest inventions ever for coffee drinkers! There have been so many times where I have wanted a cup of ground coffee (not instant), but didn't bother because I didn't want to dirty the coffee maker just for one cup, and didn't want to bother with the paper filters, etc. This pour-over filter lets you have that one cup of whatever coffee you have on hand, and you have total control over how weak or strong you want that coffee to be. However, it will hold enough ground coffee for more than one cup.

This filter is made of an ultra fine stainless steel mesh that you pour the coffee directly into, there is no need for a paper filter. The way this works is after you heat your water, place this filter over a coffee cup. This specific filter is especially nice because it has a wide base (3-5/8” or 9.2 cm diameter excluding the trim) and will fit over pretty much any drinking cup. Next, add your ground coffee into the filter. For my taste, I found that 1 heaping teaspoon of coffee is perfect. Then slowly pour your heated water directly into the filter over the coffee. There are 4 holes at the bottom of the base that enable you to see how full your coffee cup is. These holes also “catch” any coffee that has seeped through to the outside of the filter, this water will then flow through those holes right into your coffee cup. Really nice! And unlike pour-over paper filters, this does not take long to filter.

A small cleaning brush was also provided with this filter, which is nice as the brush bristles are soft and won't damage the fine stainless mesh. Another thing I like about this item is the little handle has a rubber grip to make so it is easier to pick up. I notice after looking at some of the other models they do not have the rubber grip.
This is a really nice coffee dripper/filter, and certainly worth having if you want total control over your coffee strength, or just want that one cup of coffee and don't want to mess with a coffee maker. If I could give it more than 5 stars, I would!

text:
Pros - it is space saving, is gentle on clothes (more gentle than TL models with agitator) and looks nice

Cons. Really Badly designed. Gasket in front gets moldy because the water builds up in the channels and there is no drain. Even with wiping it out after every wash, leaving the door open to air out, running sanitize cycles and using powdered soap and no fabric softener (and running sanitize cycles with bleach or vinegar), I still get mold and then my clothes smell like mold. Very high maintenance to prevent the mold and not really worth the time considering how expensive this is.

In order to clean out the lint and buildup, you have to practically take the machine apart. Mine is in a built in custom kitchen and it is a nightmare to do this. All other part that might need a regular service are also similarly inaccessible so , in addition to the high cost of purchase, there is a very high cost of maintenance.

I had combo HE front loaders in europe and never had to do more than a moment's maintenance and never had issues. This one is more trouble than it is worth.

Drying time is LONG. Like for lightweight summer sundresses and underwear and not even a full load 1.5-2 hrs long. When I can hang my clothes outside I can just about bear this thing, but when I can't, I curse it's existence with all my heart.

It came with the house I bought, but I would never buy anything like this again. I dislike it sufficiently that I am considering removing it to get back some of my cabinet space and going to the launderette.

It indicated that it had failed. Its a VERY simple install.. In fact my Wife did it for fun. She wants to learn how to fix all the things around the house as I will not be here down the road. That's a long story, but simply put, I started tobacco use at 13 years old and never quit. I am 43 now and the damage is done.. Moving along.. My Wife enjoy's tackling the different little projects around the house that most people pay technitions and repair techs a great deal of money to do. This entire repair cost us only the cost of the new part. I think it was 53 bucks here on Amazon with free Prime shipping. It took 2 days to get here and we had it installed an hour after it arrived. I have done 4 loads of laundry and the part works perfectly. The local appliance parts center wanted 109 dollars for it. WE always like to support the local guy, but over double the price was just to much for us going into the Christmas season. We are trying to save some money for the kids Christmas presents.

title: Worked well with additional repair steps
text: Used this to mend our washing machine. The drive splines on the metal shaft rusted a lot and consequently tore up this piece. That metal assembly is no longer available (machine is only 4 years old). I cleaned the shaft after disassembly with a wire wheel. I then coated the inside of this plastic gear with candle wax. After assembling the machine to the point of needing this gear I mixed up JB Weld fast set and spread it onto the metal shaft thoroughly pressing it into the pores. Then I slid this gear onto the shaft. The wax concept is to prevent the epoxy from binding to the gear should I need to make a future repair. Otherwise good luck getting it apart. Washing machines are too expensive to replace. You're paying a lot for old tech. The machines just look fancier and have more computer controls.. controls that rely on more sensors... sensors that essentially still rely on the same basic drive motor and gear assembly.

title: Giantex -  Practical Innovations for people who are not afraid to do a little extra work
text:
This was a life saver for me. After our washer stopped working and then our dryer, again, I was just so done. I decided I needed a backup as going to the laundromat is a huge problem for me time wise. My schedule is just way too hectic for that. So after trying hand washing alone and messing up my hands in the process (hello joint pain), I needed another option. This little gem did just that for me. No, you cannot wash a lot of stuff in here. I usually am able to fit in about 3-5 shirts, 2 pants (depending on the type). I can even fit sheets in there, at least 2-3 twin size and 3-4 pillowcase covers, no blankets obviously. Nevertheless, it seriously does the job. My clothes do come out much cleaner and I also noticed that when washing my clothes in this little bit of practical magic that my skin did not itch as opposed to when we use a traditional washer. Furthermore, the little spinner also does a pretty good job in that when I hang my clothes up to air dry they are done usually within an hour or two. However, I do not do a lot of loads in one day as I do wring out any excess water before adding to the spinner and that can further take a toll on my hands so I just wash at best 2-3 loads a day with this. Now I no longer keep a hamper in my bathroom I just put my things in there until I have enough for a load.
I have set up a little laundry station in my bathroom. This little baby does not take up much space. I place it in the bathtub when using and add water directly from the faucet from the tub by simply tilting it directly underneath. When the load is done I switch to drain and lift one side, let the hose hang down to drain the water and repeat until the water is out (usually takes me 2 times to completely drain). I know this sounds more cumbersome but its not a strain for me. When I'm done using I put it back in its place after its been thoroughly drained. FYI: I tend to let it sit in the tub for a little while after basically manually draining to make sure all of the water is out to prevent leaks which have not happened. It's not really heavy at all at 20lbs when empty and close to 50lb+ when fully loaded. But, I like it and I no longer have to worry if my machines conk out again.
As for the company, the product came in good time with excellent packaging. Really pleased with this purchase. I only wish I had been aware that these things existed years before.
Thank you for reading and thank you to the company!!!!!
